'''Facundo Axel Medina''' (born 28 May 1999) is an Argentine professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] or [[left-back]] for {{French football updater|Lens}} club [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], on loan from [[RC Lens|Lens]], and the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]].<ref name="Soccerway">{{cite news|title=Argentina - F. Medina|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/facundo-medina/469493/|access-date=21 September 2018|work=Soccerway}}</ref>

==Club career==
Medina's career got underway with a stint with [[Club Atlético River Plate|River Plate]], who he was an unused substitute for four times during the [[2016–17 Argentine Primera División]] season.<ref name="Soccerway"/> In January 2018, Medina completed a move to fellow [[Argentine Primera División]] side [[Talleres de Córdoba|Talleres]].<ref name="Talleres">{{cite news|title=Facundo Medina refuerza la defensa de Talleres para la Superliga|url=https://www.clubtalleres.com.ar/facundo-medina-refuerza-la-defensa-de-talleres-para-la-superliga/|access-date=21 September 2018|work=Talleres|archive-date=1 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201165737/https://www.clubtalleres.com.ar/facundo-medina-refuerza-la-defensa-de-talleres-para-la-superliga/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="BDFA">{{cite news|title=Ficha Estadistica de FACUNDO MEDINA|url=https://www.bdfa.com.ar/jugadores-FACUNDO-ALEX-MEDINA-116454.html|access-date=21 September 2018|work=BDFA}}</ref> After featuring for their U20s at the [[2018 U-20 Copa Libertadores]] in February, he made his first league appearances in August when he played in matches against [[Boca Juniors]], [[Rosario Central]] and [[Club de Gimnasia y Esgrima La Plata|Gimnasia y Esgrima]].<ref name="Soccerway"/> He scored his first senior goal in February 2020 against [[Club Atlético Huracán|Huracán]].<ref name="Soccerway"/> After a total of 37 appearances for Talleres, Medina departed in July 2020 to [[Ligue 1]] side [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref name="LEN1">{{cite news|title=Facundo Medina rejoint le RC Lens|url=https://www.rclens.fr/fr/news/mercato-contrat-facundo-medina-franck-haise-arnaud-pouille-rclens-2020702|access-date=9 July 2020|work=Lens|date=2 July 2020}}</ref>

Medina netted his first goal for Lens on 13 September against [[FC Lorient|Lorient]], scoring with an [[Bicycle kick|overhead kick]] as his side won 3–2 away from home.<ref name="Soccerway"/><ref name="IB2">{{cite news|title=Un argentino ex River y Talleres anotó de chilena el mejor gol del fin de semana en Europa|url=https://www.infobae.com/deportes/2020/09/13/un-argentino-ex-river-y-talleres-anoto-de-chilena-el-mejor-gol-del-fin-de-semana-en-europa/|access-date=19 September 2020|work=Infobae|date=13 September 2020}}</ref> He scored again on 3 February 2021 during a 2–2 draw at home to [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref name="Soccerway"/> His third Lens goal arrived on his [[Coupe de France]] starting debut in a defeat away to [[Championnat National]] club [[Red Star F.C.|Red Star]] on 6 March.<ref name="Soccerway"/> On 18 January 2023, he extended his contract with Lens until 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=2023-01-18 |title=RC Lens : Facundo Medina officiellement prolongé jusqu’en 2026 |url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/1280200/article/2023-01-18/rc-lens-facundo-medina-officiellement-prolonge-jusqu-en-2026 |access-date=2023-01-18 |website=La Voix du Nord |language=fr}}</ref>

==International career==
After playing in all three of Talleres' fixtures at the beginning of [[2018–19 Argentine Primera División|2018–19]], Medina received a call-up to the [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U20]] squad.<ref name="Mundod Lavoz 1">{{cite news|title=Facundo Medina, el lateral de Talleres que fue convocado a la selección argentina sub 20|url=http://mundod.lavoz.com.ar/futbol/facundo-medina-el-lateral-de-talleres-que-fue-convocado-la-seleccion-argentina-sub-20|access-date=21 September 2018|work=Mundod Lavoz|date=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref name="Mundod Lavoz 2">{{cite news|title=Jugó Facundo Medina de Talleres y ganó la selección sub 20|url=http://mundod.lavoz.com.ar/futbol/jugo-facundo-medina-de-talleres-y-gano-la-seleccion-sub-20|access-date=21 September 2018|work=Mundod Lavoz|date=29 August 2018}}</ref> He subsequently featured on 29 August 2018 in a friendly with [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|Uruguay]].<ref name="Mundod Lavoz 1"/><ref name="Mundod Lavoz 2"/> He had previous experience with the U20s during his time with River Plate, and was also called up to train against the [[Argentina national football team|senior squad]] during the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref name="Talleres"/><ref name="Mundod Lavoz 3">{{cite news|title=Facundo Medina, el último "propio" en sumarse a la pretemporada de Talleres|url=http://mundod.lavoz.com.ar/futbol/facundo-medina-el-ultimo-propio-en-sumarse-la-pretemporada-de-talleres|access-date=21 September 2018|work=Mundod Lavoz|date=9 July 2018}}</ref> In December, Medina was selected for the [[2019 South American U-20 Championship]].<ref name="AFA 1">{{cite news|title=Convocados para el Sudamericano Sub 20|url=http://www.afa.com.ar/11288/convocados-para-el-sudamericano-sub-20|access-date=2 January 2019|work=AFA|date=22 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102050811/http://www.afa.com.ar/11288/convocados-para-el-sudamericano-sub-20|archive-date=2 January 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was also picked for the subsequent [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup|FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref name="AFA 2">{{cite news|title=Lista de convocados para el Mundial|url=http://www.afa.com.ar/12140/lista-de-convocados-para-el-mundial|access-date=4 May 2019|work=AFA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504144225/http://www.afa.com.ar/12140/lista-de-convocados-para-el-mundial|archive-date=4 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He featured eleven times in the tournaments.<ref name="Soccerway"/> Medina was called by the [[Argentina national under-23 football team|U23s]] for the [[Football at the 2019 Pan American Games – Men's tournament|2019 Pan American Games]].<ref name="AFA 3">{{cite news|title=Lista de convocados de la Selección Sub 23 para los Juegos Panamericanos|url=https://www.afa.com.ar/es/posts/lista-de-convocados-de-la-seleccion-sub-23-para-los-juegos-panamericanos|access-date=29 July 2019|work=AFA|date=17 July 2019}}</ref>

Medina appeared in all five of Argentina's matches at the Pan American Games, as they came away with the trophy after defeating Honduras in the final.<ref name="Soccerway"/> In September 2020, having won the [[2020 CONMEBOL Pre-Olympic Tournament]] with the U23s months earlier, Medina received his first call-up to the Argentina senior squad from manager [[Lionel Scaloni]].<ref name="IB1"/> He debuted in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying victory away to [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] on 13 October, after replacing [[Lautaro Martínez]] for the final moments at the [[Estadio Hernando Siles]].<ref name="Soccerway"/>

